149. Med Law. 1991;10(2):155-83.

Abortion: in search of a constitutional doctrine (Part 1).

Leyshon DJ(1).

Author information:
(1)Rhodes University, Grahamstown, South Africa.

This article addresses the highly controversial topic of abortion from a 
constitutional angle. It discusses and analyses the landmark United States 
decision of Roe v Wade, the fundamental arguments of pro-choice and pro-life 
supporters, the difficulties inherent in the pro-choice and pro-life options and 
the abortion situation in South Africa, and concludes with proposals for a 
future Bill of Rights.

PIP: The abortion debate is very emotional and often reverts to dogmatic 
positions that are indefensible. In terms of the Constitution, abortion exists 
as an implied right of privacy under the 14th amendment. Roe v. Wade established 
this right and it did so with the support of other decisions about privacy. The 
fundamental arguments for the pro-choice side of the debate center around a 
woman's right to privacy in making decisions to abort a fetus. The fundamental 
arguments for the pro-life side of the debate center around an extension of 
Constitutional protection to the fetus. Both these positions suffer from 
difficulties in their justifications. The pro-choice side of the debate fails to 
recognize fetal viability as the fulcrum for competing rights. The pro-choice 
side of the debate fails to understand that not everyone thinks that life begins 
at conception. In South Africa a new Bill of Rights leaves the question of 
abortion unanswered. The Courts will have to decide if the Bill of Rights 
protects the rights of women to bodily integrity or protects the fetus's right 
to life.

PMID: 1886465 [Indexed for MEDLINE]


